            "answer_text": "It really depends on your situation. Here are some potential cases: Using MARGIN:In this case, all you have to do is to define a rule and apply it to your item. .my-image { margin-left: 20px; }\u00a0Using TRANSFORM:In this case, you can apply a transformation to your image and translate it on the X axis. .my-image { transform: translateX(20px) }\u00a0Using POSITION:In this situation, you need to set POSITION: RELATIVE to the element and then define the LEFT value for indentation. .my-image { position: relative; left: 20px; }\u00a0Using PADDING:In order to use padding, you will need to apply it to the parent of the image <style type=\"text/css\">\u00a0\t.my-wrapper { padding-left: 20px }\u00a0</style>\u00a0\u00a0<div class=\"my-wrapper\">\u00a0\t<img class=\"my-image\" src=\"some-image.png\" alt=\"my image\" /> \u00a0</div>\u00a0",
